{"id":"1606.01871","submitter":"Erik Martens A","authors":"Erik Andreas Martens and Christian Bick and Mark J Panaggio","title":"Chimera states in two populations with heterogeneous phase-lag","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Chaos, 26(9), 94819 (2016)","doi":"10.1063/1.4958930","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.AO nlin.CD nlin.PS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The simplest network of coupled phase-oscillators exhibiting chimera states\nis given by two populations with disparate intra- and inter-population coupling\nstrengths. We explore the effects of heterogeneous coupling phase-lags between\nthe two populations. Such heterogeneity arises naturally in various settings,\nfor example as an approximation to transmission delays, excitatory-inhibitory\ninteractions, or as amplitude and phase responses of oscillators with\nelectrical or mechanical coupling. We find that breaking the phase-lag symmetry\nresults in a variety of states with uniform and non-uniform synchronization,\nincluding in-phase and anti-phase synchrony, full incoherence (splay state),\nchimeras with phase separation of $0$ or $\\pi$ between populations, and states\nwhere both populations remain desynchronized. These desynchronized states\nexhibit stable, oscillatory, and even chaotic dynamics. Moreover, we identify\nthe bifurcations through which chimeras emerge. Stable chimera states and\ndesynchronized solutions, which do not arise for homogeneous phase-lag\nparameters, emerge as a result of competition between synchronized in-phase,\nanti-phase equilibria, and fully incoherent states when the phase-lags are near\n$\\pm\\frac{\\pi}{2}$ (cosine coupling). These findings elucidate previous\nexperimental results involving a network of mechanical oscillators and provide\nfurther insight into the breakdown of synchrony in biological systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Jun 2016 19:29:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 26 Jun 2016 08:27:47 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 11 Oct 2016 18:35:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-12"}
